{"id":"1909.03286","submitter":"Peter Dankelmann","authors":"P. Dankelmann, F.J. Osaye (University of Johannesburg)","title":"Average eccentricity, minimum degree and maximum degree in graphs","comments":"15 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Let $G$ be a connected finite graph with vertex set $V(G)$. The eccentricity\n$e(v)$ of a vertex $v$ is the distance from $v$ to a vertex farthest from $v$.\nThe average eccentricity of $G$ is defined as $\\frac{1}{|V(G)|}\\sum_{v \\in\nV(G)}e(v)$. We show that the average eccentricity of a connected graph of order\n$n$, minimum degree $\\delta$ and maximum degree $\\Delta$ does not exceed\n$\\frac{9}{4} \\frac{n-\\Delta-1}{\\delta+1}\n  \\big( 1 + \\frac{\\Delta-\\delta}{3n} \\big) + 7$, and this bound is sharp apart\nfrom an additive constant. We give improved bounds for triangle-free graphs and\nfor graphs not containing a $4$-cycles.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 7 Sep 2019 15:23:56 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-09-10"}
